Got it — this is a classic silent failure of oc cp 👍
Your command runs without error, but file is not copied → almost always means tar issue inside container.


---

🔥 Root Cause (very likely)

oc cp uses tar inside the container.
If tar is:

❌ Not installed

❌ Not in PATH

❌ Restricted (distroless / minimal image)


👉 Then copy silently fails (exactly what you're seeing)


---

✅ Step 1: Confirm the issue

Run:

oc exec -n bscf bscf125-bpp0-5bb84c8c88-bvj8g -- which tar

OR:

oc exec -n bscf bscf125-bpp0-5bb84c8c88-bvj8g -- tar --version

👉 If no output / error → that's the problem


---

🚀 Step 2: Use working workaround (BEST FIX)

✅ Copy using cat

oc exec -n bscf bscf125-bpp0-5bb84c8c88-bvj8g -- cat /root/vpms_noti.pcap > vpms_noti.pcap

Now check:

ll vpms_noti.pcap


---

🚀 Step 3: Better method (for binary files like .pcap)

Since .pcap is binary, use this safer version:

oc exec -n bscf bscf125-bpp0-5bb84c8c88-bvj8g -- base64 /root/vpms_noti.pcap | base64 -d > vpms_noti.pcap


---

🔍 Step 4: Verify file inside pod (important)

oc exec -n bscf bscf125-bpp0-5bb84c8c88-bvj8g -- ls -l /root/vpms_noti.pcap


---

🧠 Why your command showed no error

Defaulted container "bpp" out of: bpp, install (init)

👉 Only informational
👉 oc cp does NOT always throw error when tar fails → very misleading


---

💡 Pro Tip (for future)

If you're working in restricted containers (very common in OpenShift):

Always assume oc cp might fail

Prefer:

cat

base64

or tar pipe




